1307":"1307","West Ayton, Yorkshire, England":"West Ayton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Ayton, Yorkshire, England":"Ayton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Alnwick, Northumberland Unitary Authority, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Aton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Hatton  , with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>).","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Hatton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hatton (Cheshire, Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Aton I was born in 1230, in Ayton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Gilbert de Aton III, was 37 and his mother, Margerie De Vesci, was 30. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs William De Aton I. He died in 1298, in West Ayton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1230–1298":"1230–1298","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1250–1298":"1250–1298","1252–1307":"1252–1307","1193–1235":"1193–1235","1200–1235":"1200–1235","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1298":"1298","1230":"1230","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","1193":"1193","1307":"1307","West Ayton, Yorkshire, England":"West Ayton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ayton, Yorkshire, England":"Ayton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Alnwick, Northumberland Unitary Authority, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1230–1298":"1230–1298","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1250–1298":"1250–1298","1252–1307":"1252–1307","1193–1235":"1193–1235","1200–1235":"1200–1235","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1298":"1298","1230":"1230","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","1193":"1193","1307":"1307","West Ayton, Yorksh